1
00:00:44,319 --> 00:00:48,881
<i>I came to America in 1914,</i>
<i>by way of Philadelphia.</i>

2
00:00:49,090 --> 00:00:51,058
<i>That's where I got off the boat.</i>

3
00:00:51,259 --> 00:00:54,251
<i>And then I came to Baltimore.</i>

4
00:00:54,629 --> 00:00:59,464
<i>It was the most beautiful place</i>
<i>you've ever seen in your life.</i>

5
00:01:00,568 --> 00:01:03,594
<i>There were lights everywhere.</i>
<i>What lights they had!</i>

6
00:01:03,805 --> 00:01:06,365
<i>It was a celebration of lights.</i>

7
00:01:06,574 --> 00:01:09,202
<i>I thought they were for me:</i>
<i>"Sam was in America."</i>

8
00:01:10,211 --> 00:01:12,270
<i>Sam was in America.</i>

9
00:01:56,791 --> 00:02:00,989
<i>I didn't know what holiday it was,</i>
<i>but there were lights.</i>

10
00:02:01,729 --> 00:02:03,321
<i>And I walked under them.</i>

11
00:02:03,998 --> 00:02:06,523
<i>The sky exploded! People cheered!</i>

12
00:02:06,801 --> 00:02:09,167
<i>There were fireworks.</i>
<i>What a welcome it was!</i>

13
00:02:09,370 --> 00:02:11,167
<i>What a welcome!</i>

14
00:02:29,524 --> 00:02:31,287
<i>I didn't know where my brothers were.</i>

15
00:02:31,492 --> 00:02:35,758
<i>I had an address on a letter,</i>
<i>but when I went there, they'd moved.</i>

16
00:02:35,963 --> 00:02:38,090
<i>I found the man</i>
<i>who knew the name Krichinsky.</i>

17
00:02:38,299 --> 00:02:41,996
<i>He was a little man with big shoes.</i>
<i>I'll never forget him.</i>

18
00:02:42,203 --> 00:02:46,765
<i>He had such big shoes!</i>
<i>They were brand-new, beautiful shoes.</i>

19
00:02:46,974 --> 00:02:49,704
<i>He told me this was</i>
<i>how he made his living.</i>

20
00:02:49,911 --> 00:02:52,106
<i>He would break in shoes</i>
<i>for the wealthy.</i>

21
00:02:52,313 --> 00:02:55,805
<i>Stuff them with newspaper</i>
<i>and walk in them.</i>

22
00:02:56,017 --> 00:03:00,647
<i>I said, "What a country is this.</i>
<i>What a country."</i>

23
00:03:00,855 --> 00:03:04,916
<i>The wealthy didn't even have</i>
<i>to break in their own shoes.</i>

24
00:03:06,294 --> 00:03:10,731
<i>So this man with the shoes took me</i>
<i>down one street after another.</i>

25
00:03:10,932 --> 00:03:12,297
<i>We walked and walked...</i>

26
00:03:12,500 --> 00:03:16,368
<i>... and the skies would light up</i>
<i>and explode in a celebration.</i>

27
00:03:21,509 --> 00:03:24,034
<i>And then we came to Avalon.</i>

28
00:03:24,245 --> 00:03:28,807
<i>And the man with the shoes yelled,</i>
<i>"Krichinsky! Krichinsky!"</i>

29
00:03:29,650 --> 00:03:32,517
<i>And my four brothers looked down</i>
<i>and saw me.</i>

30
00:03:32,720 --> 00:03:33,778
<i>"Sam!"</i>

31
00:03:35,757 --> 00:03:36,746
<i>Sam.</i>

32
00:03:37,859 --> 00:03:39,087
<i>Sam.</i>

33
00:03:47,235 --> 00:03:51,763
And that's when I came to America.
It was the Fourth of July.

34
00:03:52,440 --> 00:03:56,274
Boy, did they used to celebrate.
Big celebrations.

35
00:03:56,477 --> 00:03:59,935
They closed the streets
and would celebrate through the night.

36
00:04:03,718 --> 00:04:06,482
What happened to the guy
who wore the big shoes?

37
00:04:06,687 --> 00:04:09,212
The funny thing is, he did it
for another two years.

38
00:04:09,423 --> 00:04:11,482
He brought his brother
into the business.

39
00:04:11,692 --> 00:04:15,492
They would walk the streets, breaking
in shoes. Then he got an idea!

40
00:04:15,696 --> 00:04:17,823
Why not make shoes that fit right?

41
00:04:18,032 --> 00:04:20,830
They became custom shoemakers:
The Solomon Brothers.

42
00:04:21,169 --> 00:04:26,072
They made shoes, pants.
And then they were a department store.

43
00:04:26,274 --> 00:04:29,243
But the Krichinsky brothers,
wallpaper hangers.

44
00:04:29,443 --> 00:04:33,743
The five Krichinsky brothers,
wallpaper hangers.

45
00:04:33,948 --> 00:04:35,939
<i>And we worked and worked</i>
<i>and worked.</i>

46
00:04:36,150 --> 00:04:38,243
<i>Except Gabriel didn't work.</i>

47
00:04:38,452 --> 00:04:42,912
<i>Gabriel used to point a lot.</i>
<i>"There's a crease, it's not straight."</i>

48
00:04:46,694 --> 00:04:49,925
He was the inspector.
He was the inspector.

49
00:04:50,364 --> 00:04:52,662
How did you all get
to be wallpaper hangers?

50
00:04:53,701 --> 00:04:55,464
It was your grandfather William.

51
00:04:55,670 --> 00:04:58,605
He came to America first
and worked in the department store...

52
00:04:58,806 --> 00:05:02,606
...where they sold wallpaper
and do wallpaper hanging for people.

53
00:05:02,810 --> 00:05:04,505
So he became a wallpaper hanger.

54
00:05:05,213 --> 00:05:09,343
And as each brother came over,
we all became wallpaper hangers.

55
00:05:11,752 --> 00:05:14,243
But on the weekend, we made music.

56
00:05:14,455 --> 00:05:15,717
What music it was!

57
00:05:16,224 --> 00:05:20,388
<i>We liked American music.</i>
<i>We were very popular ourselves.</i>

58
00:05:45,753 --> 00:05:46,742
<i>One night...</i>

59
00:05:48,256 --> 00:05:50,952
<i>... I looked across the floor</i>
<i>and I saw...</i>

60
00:05:52,226 --> 00:05:54,490
<i>... this young, lovely girl.</i>

61
00:05:55,963 --> 00:05:59,490
<i>I wasn't handsome,</i>
<i>and I didn't have a beautiful body.</i>

62
00:06:00,735 --> 00:06:03,101
<i>But when I touched a woman...</i>

63
00:06:03,304 --> 00:06:05,465
<i>... they fell in love with me.</i>

64
00:06:42,009 --> 00:06:45,604
<i>Oh, the family! How it grew.</i>
<i>The wives, the kids.</i>

65
00:06:45,813 --> 00:06:48,646
<i>Krichinskys everywhere, everywhere.</i>

66
00:06:48,950 --> 00:06:52,511
<i>So we had the family-circle meetings.</i>

67
00:06:52,853 --> 00:06:57,790
<i>We put money in the hat to bring over</i>
<i>the cousins, the aunts, the uncles.</i>

68
00:06:58,025 --> 00:07:02,553
<i>And then, out of the blue,</i>
<i>William gets the flu.</i>

69
00:07:03,264 --> 00:07:06,131
<i>It was a terrible epidemic,</i>
<i>the flu of 1919.</i>

70
00:07:06,334 --> 00:07:07,926
<i>Thousands died.</i>

71
00:07:08,135 --> 00:07:09,602
<i>William died.</i>

72
00:07:10,204 --> 00:07:12,968
<i>He was a young man.</i>
<i>He left three kids.</i>

73
00:07:14,608 --> 00:07:17,441
Sam, how many times do we
have to hear this story?

74
00:07:17,645 --> 00:07:19,909
We know this story.
We heard it before.

75
00:07:20,114 --> 00:07:23,242
If we don't tell them, they don't know.
Last year, Bill died.

76
00:07:23,451 --> 00:07:26,045
Was very warm last year
when Bill died.

77
00:07:26,253 --> 00:07:28,380
How many times
do we have to hear this?

78
00:07:28,589 --> 00:07:30,386
The children know this story.

79
00:07:30,591 --> 00:07:32,456
I'm telling them about
when I came here.

80
00:07:32,660 --> 00:07:35,356
Yeah, we know about it.
We all heard it before.

81
00:07:35,563 --> 00:07:38,589
Dad, you want to cut the turkey,
or do you want me to?

82
00:07:38,799 --> 00:07:41,996
I wanted to tell them about
when my father came here.

83
00:07:42,203 --> 00:07:45,195
You have plenty of time
to talk about your father.

84
00:07:46,907 --> 00:07:47,896
Sorry we're late.

85
00:07:48,109 --> 00:07:52,569
Another minute, we would've cut the
turkey without you and started to eat.

86
00:07:53,347 --> 00:07:55,975
To cut the turkey without me present?

87
00:07:56,183 --> 00:07:57,582
We leave the house!

88
00:07:57,785 --> 00:08:00,618
- We didn't cut the turkey.
- I heard the turkey was cut.

89
00:08:00,821 --> 00:08:02,982
I was just talking
about when Bill died.

90
00:08:03,190 --> 00:08:04,418
Thank God we are late.

91
00:08:05,526 --> 00:08:08,962
I don't understand this holiday.
I'll never understand it.

92
00:08:09,163 --> 00:08:12,621
- What's not to understand?
- Thanksgiving. Thanksgiving.

93
00:08:12,833 --> 00:08:14,528
We're giving thanks to who?

94
00:08:14,735 --> 00:08:16,669
You're giving thanks
for what you have.

95
00:08:16,871 --> 00:08:19,135
How many times do we have
to go through this?

96
00:08:19,340 --> 00:08:23,367
All I'm saying is, we had to get
the turkey and kill it to give thanks.

97
00:08:23,577 --> 00:08:26,910
If it wasn't this holiday,
we wouldn't have turkey.

98
00:08:27,114 --> 00:08:30,982
I don't eat turkey the rest
of the year. Why do I have to now?

99
00:08:31,185 --> 00:08:33,619
Mom, don't give thanks, okay?

100
00:08:33,821 --> 00:08:36,449
Time to tell the kids
when my father came to America.

101
00:08:36,657 --> 00:08:38,352
Can't it wait till later?

102
00:08:38,826 --> 00:08:40,384
They should hear this story.

103
00:08:40,594 --> 00:08:42,585
Eva, this is very tender.

104
00:08:42,797 --> 00:08:45,322
Of course it is.
It's a beautiful bird.

105
00:08:45,533 --> 00:08:49,128
The turkey was in the basement alive.
She killed it.

106
00:08:49,904 --> 00:08:52,771
We brought my father over in '25.

107
00:08:53,974 --> 00:08:58,308
- '25?
- William died in 1919. '25.

108
00:08:58,512 --> 00:09:00,844
'25? It was later than '25!

109
00:09:01,048 --> 00:09:03,573
He came the same year
we brought Bill and Edith.

110
00:09:03,784 --> 00:09:05,945
Bill and Edith came after!

111
00:09:06,153 --> 00:09:07,677
- After?
- Yeah, after.

112
00:09:07,888 --> 00:09:09,515
It was '26.

113
00:09:09,723 --> 00:09:12,487
What's the difference?
He came to America, right?

114
00:09:12,693 --> 00:09:15,787
It's a big difference
between '25 and '26.

115
00:09:15,996 --> 00:09:18,260
One is '25 and the other is '26.

116
00:09:19,967 --> 00:09:24,904
All's I'm saying is,
who cares if it was '25 or '26?

117
00:09:25,106 --> 00:09:29,475
Jules, Jules, if you stop remembering,
you forget.

118
00:09:30,044 --> 00:09:32,171
It was '26.

119
00:09:32,379 --> 00:09:35,075
I remember the excitement
when you went to meet him.

120
00:09:35,282 --> 00:09:38,740
<i>Finally, the father was coming.</i>
<i>We saved the money and sent it to him.</i>

121
00:09:38,953 --> 00:09:40,978
<i>The whole family went to the border...</i>

122
00:09:41,188 --> 00:09:43,782
<i>Jules, you were just a little kid.</i>

123
00:09:43,991 --> 00:09:45,288
<i>It was cold!</i>

124
00:09:46,127 --> 00:09:49,722
<i>We went to the marketplace.</i>
<i>It was cold. It was cold.</i>

125
00:09:49,930 --> 00:09:52,956
What are you talking about,
it was cold? It was late May.

126
00:09:53,167 --> 00:09:55,362
May? I remember cold.

127
00:09:55,569 --> 00:09:58,402
No, you're thinking of when
Irene was getting married.

128
00:09:58,606 --> 00:10:02,940
It was bitter cold then. No,
it was May 17 when your father came.

129
00:10:03,144 --> 00:10:05,169
Anyway, we went, the whole family.

130
00:10:05,379 --> 00:10:07,176
<i>The brothers, the wives, the kids.</i>

131
00:10:07,381 --> 00:10:10,077
<i>I didn't go,</i>
<i>and all the kids didn't go.</i>

132
00:10:10,284 --> 00:10:11,717
We waited in the house.

133
00:10:11,919 --> 00:10:15,821
There was such excitement.
The father, the father was coming.

134
00:10:16,023 --> 00:10:18,992
All I ever heard was,
"Wait until the father comes."

135
00:10:19,193 --> 00:10:22,424
The head of the family.
I pictured this big, powerful man.

136
00:10:22,630 --> 00:10:25,394
<i>All I'd heard was,</i>
<i>"Wait until the father comes."</i>

137
00:10:25,900 --> 00:10:28,334
<i>The father's word when he speaks...</i>

138
00:10:28,536 --> 00:10:31,096
<i>So I'm there. I see him.</i>

139
00:10:31,639 --> 00:10:35,006
<i>He's shorter than me, and I'm only 6.</i>

140
00:10:35,276 --> 00:10:37,836
<i>He was this little...</i>

141
00:10:41,682 --> 00:10:44,742
He was a little, little man.

142
00:10:46,187 --> 00:10:48,212
I never said he was big.

143
00:10:48,422 --> 00:10:50,822
But I said he was the father.

144
00:10:51,492 --> 00:10:52,720
From the day...

145
00:10:52,927 --> 00:10:56,920
<i>From the day he came to America,</i>
<i>he never had to work.</i>

146
00:10:57,131 --> 00:11:01,090
<i>Not a day in his life.</i>
<i>Each of us would give him 10 percent.</i>

147
00:11:01,302 --> 00:11:02,792
<i>Ten percent?</i>

148
00:11:04,205 --> 00:11:06,105
<i>Right? Right? Yeah.</i>

149
00:11:07,608 --> 00:11:09,405
<i>Ten percent. He was the father.</i>

150
00:11:10,344 --> 00:11:12,642
<i>He never drank water.</i>

151
00:11:13,914 --> 00:11:17,543
The entire time he was in America,
from the day he came...

152
00:11:17,751 --> 00:11:20,276
...he drank whiskey or seltzer water.

153
00:11:20,487 --> 00:11:22,751
He never drank water.

154
00:11:22,957 --> 00:11:25,926
And oh, boy, could he drink!

155
00:11:29,063 --> 00:11:32,089
What was that stuff called
he always used to drink?

156
00:11:32,299 --> 00:11:34,631
Slivovitz. Slivovitz.

157
00:11:36,136 --> 00:11:38,161
He used to call it "Block and Fall."

158
00:11:38,372 --> 00:11:41,739
You have one drink of that,
you walk one block and you fall!

159
00:11:41,942 --> 00:11:43,341
If you have one drink...

160
00:11:43,544 --> 00:11:46,638
It's such a strong drink,
it burned the gums out.

161
00:11:46,847 --> 00:11:49,577
He was funny. He was funny.
Very, very, very funny.

162
00:11:49,783 --> 00:11:51,444
How often did he drink water?

163
00:11:52,019 --> 00:11:54,579
Never, ever touched it.
How many times...?

164
00:11:54,788 --> 00:11:57,450
I'm sitting across from you,
you can't hear it?

165
00:11:59,260 --> 00:12:01,524
He never drank water!

166
00:12:01,729 --> 00:12:03,754
That means he doesn't drink.
I got it.

167
00:12:03,964 --> 00:12:06,899
You asked me, I told you.
Now I'm telling you some more.

168
00:12:07,101 --> 00:12:09,569
Occasionally, maybe,
he had some water.

169
00:12:12,873 --> 00:12:14,841
He never drank water.

170
00:12:15,042 --> 00:12:16,509
So he didn't like it.

171
00:12:16,910 --> 00:12:19,344
- He didn't like water.
- How many times?

172
00:12:19,546 --> 00:12:22,777
Hymie, Gabriel, Jules.

173
00:12:48,142 --> 00:12:51,407
Are aunts kids
before they become aunts?

174
00:12:51,612 --> 00:12:53,978
Everybody's a kid
before they become an aunt.

175
00:12:54,181 --> 00:12:57,241
They are?
I thought they just popped out.

176
00:13:03,724 --> 00:13:05,157
I've been thinking about it.

177
00:13:05,359 --> 00:13:08,157
It's a good time
we open our own business.

178
00:13:08,362 --> 00:13:10,762
Open our own business?
What, are you kidding?

179
00:13:10,964 --> 00:13:12,454
Think of the risk involved.

180
00:13:12,666 --> 00:13:15,396
We got good routes.
Why should we gamble?

181
00:13:15,602 --> 00:13:18,696
It's perfect.
We got built-in customers.

182
00:13:18,906 --> 00:13:22,774
We open our own place. We keep
the routes, but switch people to us.

183
00:13:22,976 --> 00:13:26,810
We sell the same goods,
except the money goes in our pockets.

184
00:13:27,014 --> 00:13:28,845
You don't think
Simmons will sit still?

185
00:13:29,049 --> 00:13:31,415
We open our own place,
he'll put someone on our routes.

186
00:13:31,618 --> 00:13:34,815
We'll hold on to the customers.
They like us, trust us.

187
00:13:35,022 --> 00:13:38,116
We won't hold on to everybody.
We'll lose customers.

188
00:13:38,325 --> 00:13:41,260
This is less dollars,
and we got to find new customers.

189
00:13:41,462 --> 00:13:42,895
The war is over, right?

190
00:13:43,097 --> 00:13:46,863
There's lots of people with lots
of money. It's a good time to gamble.

191
00:13:47,301 --> 00:13:48,290
Dessert!

192
00:13:49,103 --> 00:13:50,661
I hear dessert?

193
00:13:50,871 --> 00:13:52,429
I hear dessert.

194
00:13:53,273 --> 00:13:54,638
Dessert.

195
00:13:56,143 --> 00:13:57,371
Bring me dessert.

196
00:13:57,578 --> 00:13:59,205
The kids aren't having dessert?

197
00:13:59,413 --> 00:14:03,247
My grandmother is grandmother to me,
but she's not grandmother to Teddy.

198
00:14:03,450 --> 00:14:05,213
- Yes, right.
- Then what is she?

199
00:14:05,419 --> 00:14:07,080
She's Teddy's great-aunt.

200
00:14:07,287 --> 00:14:08,879
There are aunts and great-aunts?

201
00:14:09,089 --> 00:14:13,185
What's the difference between
a regular aunt and a great-aunt?

202
00:14:13,394 --> 00:14:15,362
They're older. That's the difference.

203
00:14:15,562 --> 00:14:17,257
It's not because they're older.

204
00:14:17,464 --> 00:14:21,127
Because then someday,
all aunts would be great-aunts.

205
00:14:21,335 --> 00:14:23,997
But why are great-aunts
just called great-aunts?

206
00:14:24,204 --> 00:14:27,799
Why not "good aunts" or
"fantastic aunts" or "terrible aunts"?

207
00:14:28,008 --> 00:14:32,104
No. It doesn't have anything to do
with what kind of person they are.

208
00:14:32,312 --> 00:14:36,078
It's got to do with great.
You know, they're great, older.

209
00:14:36,283 --> 00:14:39,377
What about those red ants that
crawl around and bite you?

210
00:14:39,586 --> 00:14:42,282
No, no, no. That's A-N-T.

211
00:14:42,923 --> 00:14:43,912
Ant.

212
00:14:44,892 --> 00:14:47,759
What's a first cousin, twice removed?

213
00:14:49,396 --> 00:14:51,523
I have absolutely no idea.

214
00:14:58,639 --> 00:15:01,233
I'm going selling with my dad today.

215
00:15:01,442 --> 00:15:03,273
You're not going to school?

216
00:15:03,477 --> 00:15:05,377
Christmas holidays. No school.

217
00:15:05,579 --> 00:15:07,171
Christmas holiday.

218
00:15:11,285 --> 00:15:13,651
- Keep your nose clean.
- Yeah.

219
00:15:17,825 --> 00:15:20,350
How come you didn't become
a wallpaper hanger like Sam?

220
00:15:20,561 --> 00:15:22,995
Well, Sam always had this idea...

221
00:15:23,197 --> 00:15:26,997
...that doing manual labor
had no dignity, but selling...

222
00:15:27,201 --> 00:15:30,170
"Selling was security," he said.

223
00:15:30,370 --> 00:15:32,964
No matter where you are
or what you're selling...

224
00:15:33,173 --> 00:15:34,663
...you can always make a living.

225
00:15:35,209 --> 00:15:38,940
- Can you sell anything?
- Anything. I can sell anything.

